## Summary

Implemented **simultaneous left+right mouse-click activation** following the codebase's established pure-core/live-shell seam pattern:

**New `Bringr/MouseChordActivation.swift`:**
- `MouseChordDetector` — a pure value-type state machine holding all threshold/combo logic, with a configurable threshold (default 0.12s). To satisfy AC4 (no leak), it **defers the first button press** rather than delivering it immediately — only by waiting can it distinguish a lone click from a chord-start without leaking a stray click (e.g. a right-down popping a context menu). The hold resolves to summon (partner within threshold), replay-as-normal-click (lone release or press-and-hold timeout), or release-then-rehold (late partner).
- `MouseChordMonitor` — the live `CGEventTap` that feeds real events into the detector, buffers/replays/consumes `CGEvent`s per its verdict (replays carry a sentinel so the tap ignores its own re-injection), and fires the summon. Requires Accessibility; `start()` degrades gracefully when untrusted and retries when permission flips.

**`Bringr/AppDelegate.swift`:** wires the monitor in (guarded out of XCTest), `onChord` toggles the radial menu at `NSEvent.mouseLocation` (AC3), with a Combine retry on `permissions.$isTrusted`.

**`BringrTests/MouseChordTests.swift`:** 15 tests driving the detector with synthetic events in full isolation from the live stream (AC5).

**Quality gates:** build SUCCEEDED · swiftlint `--strict` 0 violations · 68 tests pass (15 new) · app launches stably and the tap-install path degrades gracefully (verified `tap started = false` on this untrusted dev build via temporary instrumentation, then reverted — the trusted chord/overlay path isn't headlessly verifiable, which the unit tests cover instead).

Bead `Bringr-93j.7` closed; learnings appended to `progress.md`. No commit created (left for the engine).

